we're really missing the boat

00:16:47.540 --> 00:16:50.890
when it comes to understanding
our strengths.

00:16:50.890 --> 00:16:55.190
And so this activity that I
suggest, it takes two minutes,

00:16:55.190 --> 00:16:58.730
it is not a hard thing
to ask other people.

00:16:58.730 --> 00:17:02.170
Basically, what it entails is
over the course of the next week

00:17:02.170 --> 00:17:07.610
or so ask about let's say half a
dozen people, friends, colleagues,

00:17:07.610 --> 00:17:09.340
people who know you decently well.

00:17:09.340 --> 00:17:13.640
I mean ask them this question,
if you had to describe me

00:17:13.640 --> 00:17:17.860
in only three words
what would they be?

00:17:17.860 --> 00:17:20.890
It's pretty simple, pretty fast,
it takes them a minute to answer,

00:17:20.890 --> 00:17:24.480
and they should in fact answer
off the top of their head.

00:17:24.480 --> 00:17:29.650 position:56%
But what becomes telling about it
is by the time you get to the third,

00:17:29.650 --> 00:17:33.130
the fourth, the fifth person
I guarantee you are going

00:17:33.130 --> 00:17:37.940
to see patterns in what they are
saying and you'll begin to get more

00:17:37.940 --> 00:17:41.520
of an understanding of
what other people see

00:17:41.520 --> 00:17:47.160
as being uniquely different,
uniquely meaningful about you,

00:17:47.160 --> 00:17:52.930
begins to give you some clues about
strengths that you can leverage.

00:17:52.930 --> 00:17:57.790
But I also want to point out your
strengths are an important building

00:17:57.790 --> 00:18:02.720
block, but it's not the whole game.

00:18:02.720 --> 00:18:07.590
This is a woman that I profile in
Reinventing You named Libby Wagner,

00:18:07.590 --> 00:18:13.670
and I loved telling Libby's story
in the book because oftentimes

00:18:13.670 --> 00:18:17.200
when we hear reinvention
stories there's kind of a way

00:18:17.200 --> 00:18:20.990
that they go typically in
the American psyche, right?

00:18:20.990 --> 00:18:24.140
And the way that a story

00:18:24.140 --> 00:18:27.240
about reinvention typically
goes is you have someone

00:18:27.240 --> 00:18:29.920
who is this hard charging
professional, you know,

00:18:29.920 --> 00:18:32.170
they're a management
consultant, let's say,

00:18:32.170 --> 00:18:35.940
and they really do some
soul-searching and they say,

00:18:35.940 --> 00:18:40.160
all right, I'm going to do
what I am passionate about

00:18:40.160 --> 00:18:42.980
and they go off and
they become a poet.

00:18:42.980 --> 00:18:45.980
And we tell the story, and we
say, oh, that's so amazing,

00:18:45.980 --> 00:18:48.300
they found what they
were meant to do,

00:18:48.300 --> 00:18:51.010
they lived the dream
and we celebrate that.

00:18:51.010 --> 00:18:53.510
And that is worth celebrating,
that's a great thing,

00:18:53.510 --> 00:18:57.550
we should all be doing things
we are passionate about.

00:18:57.550 --> 00:19:04.310
But what I liked about Libby's
story is that that story,

00:19:04.310 --> 00:19:08.130
the archetypal one,
it's not the only story.

00:19:08.130 --> 00:19:15.740
Libby was a poet, she had an MFA,
she was a University Professor,

00:19:15.740 --> 00:19:18.260 position:56%
she published three books of poetry.

00:19:18.260 --> 00:19:21.720
She was established,
she was successful.

00:19:21.720 --> 00:19:26.740
She decided to give it
all up, quit her job,

00:19:26.740 --> 00:19:28.910
and she became a Management
Consultant.

00:19:28.910 --> 00:19:36.570 position:56%
[laughter] And to tell you the truth
that's actually even harder to do.

00:19:36.570 --> 00:19:41.630
We can understand why a Management
Consultant might want to be a poet,

00:19:41.630 --> 00:19:44.440
but no one understood
why Libby wanted

00:19:44.440 --> 00:19:46.660
to become a Management Consultant.

00:19:46.660 --> 00:19:51.230
But she was interested
in making change,

00:19:51.230 --> 00:19:55.540
and she thought an organization
is a place you can really do it.

00:19:55.540 --> 00:20:00.830 position:56%
But she was worried, she thought
that no one would take her seriously

00:20:00.830 --> 00:20:02.230
if they knew that she was a poet,

00:20:02.230 --> 00:20:05.130
that that was her training
and her background.

00:20:05.130 --> 00:20:09.150
So her solution to it was
she didn't tell anyone,

00:20:09.150 --> 00:20:11.040
she literally kept it a secret

00:20:11.040 --> 00:20:12.960
for the first few years
she was in business.

00:20:12.960 --> 00:20:15.900
She did not talk about
her background, at all,

00:20:15.900 --> 00:20:23.190
and she told me she basically
lived in fear of discovery.

00:20:23.190 --> 00:20:28.000
But slowly over time she began to
realize that nobody cared too much,

00:20:28.000 --> 00:20:33.390
nobody was badgering her, asking,
well, where did you get your MBA?

00:20:33.390 --> 00:20:35.350
What they cared about was results,

00:20:35.350 --> 00:20:39.210
and she was getting
results for people.

00:20:39.210 --> 00:20:44.950 position:56%
And a little more time passed and
she began to realize something else,

00:20:44.950 --> 00:20:49.690
which is that even though it
was very true that the people

00:20:49.690 --> 00:20:53.490
who had MBAs and had
traditional training had things

00:20:53.490 --> 00:20:58.800
that Libby didn't, she
had things they didn't.

00:20:58.800 --> 00:21:04.430
She began to realize that if you
are a corporate CEO and, let's say,

00:21:04.430 --> 00:21:08.810
you have some sensitive
communication that you want to get

00:21:08.810 --> 00:21:13.520
across well, thoughtfully,
effectively to your staff,

00:21:13.520 --> 00:21:16.680
to your customers, to
your stakeholders, maybe,

00:21:16.680 --> 00:21:20.480
just maybe the person
you actually want to have

00:21:20.480 --> 00:21:25.250
on your side is the person who has
spent a lifetime immersing herself

00:21:25.250 --> 00:21:29.070
in language and who
has trained for years

00:21:29.070 --> 00:21:32.650
to understand the nuance of words.

00:21:32.650 --> 00:21:36.320
And so she slowly began
to come out as a poet,

00:21:36.320 --> 00:21:39.850
she would tell a few people
at first and then a few more.

00:21:39.850 --> 00:21:42.810
Eventually, she started an
e-mail newsletter called The

00:21:42.810 --> 00:21:45.110
Boardroom Poet.

00:21:45.110 --> 00:21:50.190
Eventually, she started to
have workshops about language

00:21:50.190 --> 00:21:54.400
and literature and business
and how they all fit together,

00:21:54.400 --> 00:21:56.820
and she began to realize that what

00:21:56.820 --> 00:22:01.270
in her mind had been
her biggest weakness,

00:22:01.270 --> 00:22:03.940
the thing she was most
afraid of having discovered,

00:22:03.940 --> 00:22:05.240
the fact that she had trained

00:22:05.240 --> 00:22:08.940
as a poet actually
could become a strength

00:22:08.940 --> 00:22:11.200
and a competitive advantage.

00:22:11.200 --> 00:22:14.030
So when we're discovering
us, when we are thinking

00:22:14.030 --> 00:22:18.790
about who we are now, what
our current brand is it pays

00:22:18.790 --> 00:22:23.930
to understand our strengths,
but it also pays to think

00:22:23.930 --> 00:22:29.750
about our weaknesses because those
may be like Libby our strengths

00:22:29.750 --> 00:22:33.820
in disguise if we frame
it the right way and begin

00:22:33.820 --> 00:22:35.390
to understand it in that light.

00:22:35.390 --> 00:22:41.790
But, of course, that's just the
first part, discovering our brand.

00:22:41.790 --> 00:22:46.700
What comes next is creating
it, proactively thinking

00:22:46.700 --> 00:22:52.020
about who we want to be, how
we want to be known to others.

00:22:52.020 --> 00:22:55.680
And so I wanted to share
a few stories with you.

00:22:55.680 --> 00:22:58.440
This is a gentleman
named Michael Lecky.

00:22:58.440 --> 00:23:06.030
Michael is someone that I profiled
in my most recent book, Stand Out.

00:23:06.030 --> 00:23:10.410
And I was interested in
his story because in a lot

00:23:10.410 --> 00:23:14.070
of ways it's a situation
that many of us face.

00:23:14.070 --> 00:23:17.910
Michael was an executive in
a large research company,

00:23:17.910 --> 00:23:23.200 position:56%
he was a Vice President of Human
Resources, and he had responsibility

00:23:23.200 --> 00:23:27.510
for a lot of different things
related to talent development.

00:23:27.510 --> 00:23:32.590 position:56%
He began to become really
interested in coaching and training.

00:23:32.590 --> 00:23:37.160
Now this was something that was
kind of related to his job duties,

00:23:37.160 --> 00:23:39.830
but it wasn't part of his
official job description.

00:23:39.830 --> 00:23:45.360 position:56%
He was certainly not responsible
for getting good at coaching people,

00:23:45.360 --> 00:23:49.330
that was not really
something that he needed

00:23:49.330 --> 00:23:51.820
to do, but it fascinated him.

00:23:51.820 --> 00:23:55.850
He was interested in it, he
wanted to learn more about it.

00:23:55.850 --> 00:24:00.830 position:56%
And so his company had hired an
outside consultant that they brought

00:24:00.830 --> 00:24:03.890
in to help with coaching,
and Michael took his course,

00:24:03.890 --> 00:24:05.510
thought it was really great.

00:24:05.510 --> 00:24:12.100
And so because he started with
a spark of interest he decided

00:24:12.100 --> 00:24:14.380
to follow it up and
see where it led.

00:24:14.380 --> 00:24:16.700
So he reached out to the
consultant and he said, hey,

00:24:16.700 --> 00:24:21.620
the next time you're offering this
could I help you, could I assist?

00:24:21.620 --> 00:24:24.350
And he started in small
ways, you know,

00:24:24.350 --> 00:24:28.210
you can start by helping people
set up or break down or clean up,

00:24:28.210 --> 00:24:32.570
you can start by helping
people make handouts

00:24:32.570 --> 00:24:36.270 position:56%
or lead discussion groups at tables.

00:24:36.270 --> 00:24:42.510
But he volunteered to assist,
and before too long he started

00:24:42.510 --> 00:24:45.350
to make himself indispensable,
he was pretty helpful.

00:24:45.350 --> 00:24:50.580 position:56%
And so he began to co-lead the
seminars and over time he got better

00:24:50.580 --> 00:24:54.590
and better, and he eventually
began leading them himself.

00:24:54.590 --> 00:25:01.290 position:56%
Now what happened inside his company
is that before too long he began

00:25:01.290 --> 00:25:06.160
to really develop a reputation as
the person inside his organization

00:25:06.160 --> 00:25:09.040
who knew about coaching
and training.

00:25:09.040 --> 00:25:11.110
He didn't start out that
way, he didn't start

00:25:11.110 --> 00:25:15.850
out with any more knowledge than
anyone else, but he had an interest

00:25:15.850 --> 00:25:17.960
and a willingness to learn.

00:25:17.960 --> 00:25:22.220
And what he told me when I
interviewed him for Stand Out is

00:25:22.220 --> 00:25:29.100
that if you are humble and
recognize where you're coming from,

00:25:29.100 --> 00:25:32.150
you can't immediately start out
and say, oh, I'm the expert,

00:25:32.150 --> 00:25:35.760
but if you're clear about what
you know and what you don't know

00:25:35.760 --> 00:25:37.810
and you're willing to
share that knowledge

00:25:37.810 --> 00:25:42.030
with others along the way
they're going to be appreciative

00:25:42.030 --> 00:25:47.150
and they're going to start to
seek you out because you're going

00:25:47.150 --> 00:25:50.380
to become a big fish
in a small pond.

00:25:50.380 --> 00:25:53.240
You don't have to know the most
about coaching and training

00:25:53.240 --> 00:25:56.830
in the world, but if you
know more than the people

00:25:56.830 --> 00:26:00.410
around you you make
yourself an invaluable

00:26:00.410 --> 00:26:02.700
and indispensable resource.

00:26:02.700 --> 00:26:06.760
It doesn't take a lot to
develop and expert reputation,

00:26:06.760 --> 00:26:11.810
just a little focus, just a little
humility, just a little willingness

00:26:11.810 --> 00:26:18.060
to tell other people and help
them along with you as you learn.

00:26:18.060 --> 00:26:22.310
One of the other pieces that
becomes critical as we think

00:26:22.310 --> 00:26:28.170 position:56%
about how we get known for the brand
that we want, how to begin spreading

00:26:28.170 --> 00:26:31.100
that inside and outside
our organizations,

00:26:31.100 --> 00:26:35.010
is the circle of people
that you have around you.

00:26:35.010 --> 00:26:39.190
This is a woman that I profile
in Stand Out named Cary Anderson.

00:26:39.190 --> 00:26:42.370
And I've known Cary
for a number of years,

00:26:42.370 --> 00:26:46.550
and one day she told
me something that was

00:26:46.550 --> 00:26:50.460
so unusual it just
captured my attention,

00:26:50.460 --> 00:26:53.880
and I thought I have
to tell this story.

00:26:53.880 --> 00:26:55.180
And here's what it was.

00:26:55.180 --> 00:27:01.520
A lot of people have mastermind
groups, you could call them,

00:27:01.520 --> 00:27:03.380
personal Boards of Directors.

00:27:03.380 --> 00:27:08.700
This is a concept that goes
back 80 plus years to the world

00:27:08.700 --> 00:27:11.500
of Napoleon Hill, you know,
little groups of people

00:27:11.500 --> 00:27:14.830
that get together regularly to
hold each other accountable,

00:27:14.830 --> 00:27:17.270
talk about their businesses,
et cetera.

00:27:17.270 --> 00:27:20.900 position:56%
That's, you know, it's a cool thing,
but it's not an uncommon thing.

00:27:20.900 --> 00:27:23.390
So Cary has a couple of those,

00:27:23.390 --> 00:27:29.420
but the part that was amazingly
uncommon is she told me

00:27:29.420 --> 00:27:35.230
that one group that she's been
meeting with was formed in 1989

00:27:35.230 --> 00:27:42.700
and the other in 1994 and they have
been meeting every single month

00:27:42.700 --> 00:27:49.550
since then, now for more than
20 years and more than 25 years.

00:27:49.550 --> 00:27:54.000
she told me that the people in
these groups with her outside

00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:58.270
of her immediate family are
the people that know her best

00:27:58.270 --> 00:28:02.360
in the entire world
and that participation

00:28:02.360 --> 00:28:07.500
in the group has become for
her the defining characteristic

00:28:07.500 --> 00:28:12.620
of her professional life because
they are the people that know her

00:28:12.620 --> 00:28:16.520
so well, when they give her
feedback, when they give her ideas,

00:28:16.520 --> 00:28:19.190
when they push back
on her a little bit,

00:28:19.190 --> 00:28:24.280
she knows that she can trust it
implicitly because they know her

00:28:24.280 --> 00:28:30.350
so well and they have no agenda,
they have her best interests

00:28:30.350 --> 00:28:34.980
at heart, which is something
that perhaps too often

00:28:34.980 --> 00:28:38.570
in our modern life we lack.

00:28:38.570 --> 00:28:46.560
Now what Cary's story bring sup for
me is this, when I talk to groups

00:28:46.560 --> 00:28:50.390
of professionals I'll ask
them sometimes, you know,

00:28:50.390 --> 00:28:52.350
who do you spend time with?

00:28:52.350 --> 00:28:55.570
Who are the people that
you surround yourself with,

00:28:55.570 --> 00:28:59.880
the people that you have lunches
and meetings and coffee with?

00:28:59.880 --> 00:29:05.500 position:56%
And oftentimes what I hear is, well,
it's the people who e-mailed me

00:29:05.500 --> 00:29:11.790
and asked or it's the people
that I happen to sit next to,

00:29:11.790 --> 00:29:15.960
it's the people that I happen
to be working on a project with.

00:29:17.210 --> 00:29:22.660
If our professional lives
are defined by the people

00:29:22.660 --> 00:29:29.350
that we connect with, why so
often do we leave that to chance?

00:29:29.350 --> 00:29:32.820
We need to start getting
deliberate about who we want

00:29:32.820 --> 00:29:36.980
to surround ourselves with, who
we want to be learning from.

00:29:36.980 --> 00:29:41.940
And so I will challenge
you, as you go home today,

00:29:41.940 --> 00:29:46.070
go back to your desks, to ask
yourself who are the people,

00:29:46.070 --> 00:29:54.160 position:56%
the three or five or seven people in
your life that you respect the most,

00:29:54.160 --> 00:30:02.010
that you want most to learn from,
the people whose skills you wish

00:30:02.010 --> 00:30:04.680
that you could be more like?

00:30:04.680 --> 00:30:08.340
How can you arrange it proactively

00:30:08.340 --> 00:30:11.600
to spend more time
with those people?

00:30:11.600 --> 00:30:17.330
We learn through osmosis,
we learn through presence.

00:30:17.330 --> 00:30:22.420
How can we change our behavior
just a little bit so that we can be

00:30:22.420 --> 00:30:27.450
around the people who bring
out the best in ourselves?

00:30:27.450 --> 00:30:30.410
Because the truth is
those are the people

00:30:30.410 --> 00:30:33.390
who can become your
brand ambassadors,

00:30:33.390 --> 00:30:37.300 position:56%
the people who can give you the
feedback you need to take your ideas

00:30:37.300 --> 00:30:40.370
to the next level, and
the people who inside

00:30:40.370 --> 00:30:44.180
and outside your organization
can represent you to other people

00:30:44.180 --> 00:30:50.130
and help you get the opportunities
that are dearest to your goals.

00:30:50.130 --> 00:30:55.190
Now in this professional
world that we live

00:30:55.190 --> 00:31:00.970
in what we're fundamentally
known for is our ideas,

00:31:00.970 --> 00:31:03.460
and this can be a little
bit tricky sometimes

00:31:03.460 --> 00:31:07.310
because ideas are ineffable, right?

00:31:07.310 --> 00:31:12.600
How do we know if somebody's
ideas are good?

00:31:12.600 --> 00:31:14.900
We have to share them.

00:31:14.900 --> 00:31:19.520
We have to find ways of expressing
them and we have to really think

00:31:19.520 --> 00:31:25.590
about how we can start prompting
ourselves to think differently

00:31:25.590 --> 00:31:29.930
so that the ideas that we generate
are not just the same thing

00:31:29.930 --> 00:31:32.440
that everyone else is doing.

00:31:32.440 --> 00:31:37.350
You know, in a global networked
world the world doesn't need more

00:31:37.350 --> 00:31:42.350
of the same, the world needs
people who are suggesting things

00:31:42.350 --> 00:31:45.090
that other people haven't
seen or thought of yet.

00:31:45.090 --> 00:31:49.340
But the question is how do we
put ourselves into that state?

00:31:49.340 --> 00:31:53.700
How do we make that
more likely to happen?

00:31:53.700 --> 00:31:56.670
And so I wanted to share with
you a story about someone

00:31:56.670 --> 00:32:00.210
who actually is a local,
at least originally.

00:32:00.210 --> 00:32:02.510
Her name is Rose Schuman
[Assumed Spelling] and she grew

00:32:02.510 --> 00:32:05.000
up in the suburbs of Maryland.

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:09.780
Now up until when she was about
18 years old she had a pretty

00:32:09.780 --> 00:32:12.770
traditional upbringing
in suburban Maryland,

00:32:12.770 --> 00:32:18.030
but when she was 18 she took
a family trip to Nicaragua,

00:32:18.030 --> 00:32:20.210
which is where her
stepmother was from,

00:32:20.210 --> 00:32:22.820 position:56%
to go visit the stepmother's family.

00:32:22.820 --> 00:32:28.320
And that was something that
changed the course of her life.

00:32:28.320 --> 00:32:32.340
It was shortly after the end
of the Contra War in Nicaragua,

00:32:32.340 --> 00:32:36.770
and when she went there the
country was in disarray.

00:32:36.770 --> 00:32:41.840
There was one functioning
streetlight in the entire country.

00:32:41.840 --> 00:32:46.670
The systems, the institutions that
she had taken for granted growing

00:32:46.670 --> 00:32:51.350
up 20 miles from here
were nowhere to be found.

00:32:51.350 --> 00:32:55.630
And that was when she decided
she wanted to devote her life

00:32:55.630 --> 00:32:59.540
to development work,
and that's what she did.

00:32:59.540 --> 00:33:02.560
She went to school for
it and she graduated.

00:33:02.560 --> 00:33:04.810
Took a job with an NGO.

00:33:04.810 --> 00:33:10.650 position:56%
And so a few years later she found
herself one day walking around town,

00:33:10.650 --> 00:33:14.830
wandering around, and she
was thinking about a puzzle,

00:33:14.830 --> 00:33:19.890
a problem that had occupied
her for years and, in fact,

00:33:19.890 --> 00:33:24.230
it had occupied a lot of people
for years, which was the question

00:33:24.230 --> 00:33:28.990
of how can we harness
the power of the internet

00:33:28.990 --> 00:33:31.990
for the world's poorest people?

00:33:31.990 --> 00:33:35.350
Now there had been a lot of
reasonably good solutions to that.

00:33:35.350 --> 00:33:36.780
Many of you may, for instance,

00:33:36.780 --> 00:33:39.990
have heard of the one
laptop per child initiative,

00:33:39.990 --> 00:33:41.360
pretty good idea, right?

00:33:41.360 --> 00:33:44.790
Cheap laptops, give them
to people, it's great,

00:33:44.790 --> 00:33:48.830
but that's not still
a perfect solution,

00:33:48.830 --> 00:33:53.820
particularly if we're talking about
the poorest people in the world.

