study is that it turns out,

00:52:20.610 --> 00:52:28.600 position:56%
they surveyed LGBT employees and
they asked them do you feel isolated

00:52:28.600 --> 00:52:32.960
at work, do you feel
stalled in your career?

00:52:32.960 --> 00:52:38.990 position:56%
And you might think that openly gay
employees would maybe be feeling the

00:52:38.990 --> 00:52:43.500
brunt of this, that
they had taken a risk,

00:52:43.500 --> 00:52:47.170
that they might be
paying a penalty for it.

00:52:47.170 --> 00:52:50.310
I mean, after all, that's why
people stay in the closet, right,

00:52:50.310 --> 00:52:56.460
is because they feel that there's
a risk and a penalty to being out.

00:52:56.460 --> 00:53:04.120
It turns out, ironically, that
out employees were far happier

00:53:04.120 --> 00:53:09.000
and more successful than
their closeted brethren.

00:53:09.000 --> 00:53:12.910
Now I'm putting a big
asterisk on this because,

00:53:12.910 --> 00:53:17.900
of course unfortunately, we
still live in a country in which

00:53:17.900 --> 00:53:23.500
in many states people can still
be fired legally for being out.

00:53:23.500 --> 00:53:28.240
But in situations where that
is not the case, where state

00:53:28.240 --> 00:53:33.230
or a company has an
antidiscrimination policy,

00:53:33.230 --> 00:53:35.990
these are pretty stark numbers.

00:53:35.990 --> 00:53:40.560
If you are out you
are less isolated.

00:53:40.560 --> 00:53:45.180
If you are out you are more likely
to be successful in your career.

00:53:45.180 --> 00:53:48.910
Why? How could that be?

00:53:48.910 --> 00:53:52.570
Well, it turns out that
what they discovered is

00:53:52.570 --> 00:53:57.880
that when people are holding
back a fundamental element

00:53:57.880 --> 00:54:06.600 position:56%
of who they are it occupies so much
of their psyche it's actually harder

00:54:06.600 --> 00:54:10.850
for them to concentrate on
other elements of their job,

00:54:10.850 --> 00:54:15.520
like building positive, open
connections with their coworkers.

00:54:15.520 --> 00:54:19.130
People feel like they don't
really fully know you,

00:54:19.130 --> 00:54:20.870
there's a little bit of a distance.

00:54:20.870 --> 00:54:25.520
And so it's harder to
connect and break through.

00:54:25.520 --> 00:54:30.840
Now that's a piece
about LGBT employees,

00:54:30.840 --> 00:54:35.180
but let me tell you how
it applies to everyone.

00:54:35.180 --> 00:54:39.780
Deloitte University and
the Leadership Center

00:54:39.780 --> 00:54:43.210
for Inclusion did an
interesting study along

00:54:43.210 --> 00:54:47.100
with Professor Kenji Yoshino
of New York University,

00:54:47.100 --> 00:54:49.630
and it's on a subject
called covering.

00:54:49.630 --> 00:54:54.140
This is based on work that
originated in the 1950s

00:54:54.140 --> 00:54:57.240
with a famous Sociologist
named Erving Goffman,

00:54:57.240 --> 00:54:59.850
and they've expanded
it and updated it.

00:54:59.850 --> 00:55:05.350
And basically what covering is
if you think about the LGBT case,

00:55:05.350 --> 00:55:09.860
when you're closeted you are
totally saying, you know,

00:55:09.860 --> 00:55:13.780
you're totally not telling
anyone about your identity,

00:55:13.780 --> 00:55:17.230
but covering would be maybe
a less extreme example.

00:55:17.230 --> 00:55:19.700
People might know that you're gay,

00:55:19.700 --> 00:55:25.940
but you are minimizing their
exposure to that identity,

00:55:25.940 --> 00:55:29.180
so maybe everybody else has
a picture of their partner

00:55:29.180 --> 00:55:32.350
on their desk but you don't
or everybody else talks

00:55:32.350 --> 00:55:35.230
about what they did with
their spouse over the weekend

00:55:35.230 --> 00:55:38.410
and you don't, you say I and not we

00:55:38.410 --> 00:55:41.110
or whatever it is,
that would be covering.

00:55:41.110 --> 00:55:44.790
But that's not just a gay thing.

00:55:44.790 --> 00:55:49.450
What the Deloitte and NYU
research discovered is

00:55:49.450 --> 00:55:55.680
that in the modern workplace
almost everyone covers

00:55:55.680 --> 00:55:58.470
in one way or another.

00:55:58.470 --> 00:56:04.630 position:56%
They found examples of
African-American or Latino employees

00:56:04.630 --> 00:56:08.650
that felt a need to play
down their cultural identity

00:56:08.650 --> 00:56:10.370
in order to fit in.

00:56:10.370 --> 00:56:15.340
They found examples of women
who were just a little careful

00:56:15.340 --> 00:56:19.410
about talking about their
families or their kids at work

00:56:19.410 --> 00:56:21.810
because they worried they
might not be perceived

00:56:21.810 --> 00:56:26.430
as a really serious worker if
they were also seen as a mom.

00:56:26.430 --> 00:56:31.900
And perhaps shockingly but
not really if you think

00:56:31.900 --> 00:56:39.710
about it the study showed
that 46% of white men,

00:56:39.710 --> 00:56:46.960
46% of straight white men reported
covering in one fashion or another.

00:56:46.960 --> 00:56:51.010
When I first gave a talk, in
fact, about this a gentleman came

00:56:51.010 --> 00:56:58.260
up to me afterwards and he said
what you talked about, that's me.

00:56:58.260 --> 00:57:01.200
He said about 10 years
ago I got divorced

00:57:01.200 --> 00:57:06.100
and I became a single father
responsible for my kids,

00:57:06.100 --> 00:57:11.910
I never told my coworkers because
I didn't want them to think

00:57:11.910 --> 00:57:13.770
that I would be distracted.

00:57:13.770 --> 00:57:18.120
It could be health issues, it
could be mental health issues,

00:57:18.120 --> 00:57:24.110
it could be almost anything, but
in our workforce even though we are

00:57:24.110 --> 00:57:29.070
in an era now where what we need
more than ever is difference

00:57:29.070 --> 00:57:36.860 position:56%
and individuality and being real too
often we find ourselves in a place

00:57:36.860 --> 00:57:41.930
where we're just a little bit
hesitant to go that final mile

00:57:41.930 --> 00:57:49.540
and really be that real because
we think that we need in some ways

00:57:49.540 --> 00:57:57.020
to still hew to that man in
the gray flannel suit ideal.

00:57:57.020 --> 00:58:04.190
What the Deloitte and NYU study
revealed is that covering,

00:58:04.190 --> 00:58:08.930 position:56%
no matter who is doing it, if you're
gay, if you're African-American

00:58:08.930 --> 00:58:14.070
or Hispanic, if you're a woman,
if you are a straight white man,

00:58:14.070 --> 00:58:19.380
when you are covering you
are less effective at work.

00:58:19.380 --> 00:58:23.060
You're not able to really
form the relationships,

00:58:23.060 --> 00:58:27.620
the honest relationships with
your colleagues that you need

00:58:27.620 --> 00:58:33.910
to be successful, you're not really
able to bring your best ideas

00:58:33.910 --> 00:58:40.110 position:56%
to the table because we become so
concerned about managing perceptions

00:58:40.110 --> 00:58:46.110
and managing our identity rather
than our jobs and really being able

00:58:46.110 --> 00:58:50.410
to be fully present to excel there.

00:58:50.410 --> 00:58:59.220 position:56%
and so what I want to leave you with
is as we think about how to stand

00:58:59.220 --> 00:59:01.870
out at work, this process

00:59:01.870 --> 00:59:08.450 position:56%
of understanding what our current
brand is, creating the future vision

00:59:08.450 --> 00:59:10.420
that we want and moving
towards that,

00:59:10.420 --> 00:59:16.600
and then finally living it out,
every day taking those steps,

00:59:16.600 --> 00:59:23.700
we need to not be afraid to
bring our whole selves to work.

00:59:23.700 --> 00:59:29.620
the more we do that the more we
empower other people to do it,

00:59:29.620 --> 00:59:33.680
and the more we can create the
kind of culture that is beneficial,

00:59:33.680 --> 00:59:38.370
not just for us but for
making the entire workplace,

00:59:38.370 --> 00:59:42.410
the entire company, the
entire culture better.

00:59:42.410 --> 00:59:46.160
What we need more of is
people willing to stand out

00:59:46.160 --> 00:59:52.440
and to be authentic, and it
starts with us and the decisions

00:59:52.440 --> 00:59:56.840
that we make, that's how
we can stand out at work.

